@sgillies I know you have said multiple times that you don't want to fix this .., but 1) it's a small change, 2) we basically do this for Linux/Mac as well (by first checking the wheel path) and 3) solves troubling import issues that can easily be avoided. 
So therefore I don't see much reason to *not* do this for Shapely 1.8 (it will still take a while until 2.0 is fully stabilized and released)

Related discussion in https://github.com/Toblerity/Shapely/pull/843#discussion_r386275247 (and also #1105, #924)

Background: see #176. We're depending on this function in 1.4.0, which breaks compatibility with GEOS 3.2.

@jwass can you think of a way to get coordinate dimension without that GEOS function?

For speedups: I propose we require GEOS 3.3+ for the speedups and vectorized modules. @olt @mwtoews @pelson agree or disagree?

Fixed regression identified by @jwass in PR https://github.com/Toblerity/Shapely/pull/170, where trying to create a LinearRing from a LineString that was not closed would cause a segfault.

The new code does a check to see if the LineString is a ring (GEOSisRing). If it is, the coordinate system is cloned and a LinearRing geometry is created. If it isn't, the function continues and the ring is closed later (https://github.com/snorfalorpagus/Shapely/blob/649fff87fc0740e9e92462feb75a79832bf8a62d/shapely/geometry/polygon.py#L425).

@jwass Could you confirm that this fixes the issue? I used is_ring instead of is_closed. Not sure of the difference, and is_closed wasn't implemented in ctypes whereas is_ring was.
